 are designed to manage risk and prevent adverse selection, ensuring that only eligible policyholders can access the enhanced benefit structure. [Data: Relationships (44), Relationships (45); Entities (33), Entities (34)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The transition between options is governed by structured policy rules\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The process of switching from Option A to Option B is not automatic and is subject to formal policy procedures. The requirement for Evidence of Insurability ensures that the policyholder’s insurability is re-evaluated, which may involve medical exams or health disclosures. The $50 processing fee further reinforces the administrative and financial weight of the change. These controls reflect a risk-mitigation strategy by the insurer, balancing policyholder flexibility with financial and underwriting integrity. The structured nature of the transition underscores the importance of the Specified Amount as a stable reference point across both options. [Data: Relationships (44), Relationships (45); Entities (33), Entities (34)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Specified Amount remains unchanged during option transitions\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Despite changes in the death benefit structure, the Specified Amount remains fixed and unadjusted when switching between Option A and Option B. It is not modified by market performance or policy amendments unless explicitly altered through a formal policy amendment, which may require underwriting approval. This stability ensures that the foundational value used for surrender charge calculations and Option A’s death benefit remains consistent, even as the overall benefit structure evolves. The persistence of the Specified Amount across options reinforces its role as a core policy element. [Data: Entities (27), Relationships (42)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Surrender charges are calculated based on the